@startuml USB Message Flow

title USB Controller — Host Link, Streaming & Command Routing

skinparam defaultFontSize 12
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam sequenceMessageAlign center
skinparam ParticipantPadding 16
skinparam BoxPadding 12
skinparam sequence {
    LifeLineBorderColor #2C7BB6
    ArrowColor #1A5276
    ArrowFontColor #1A5276
    ArrowFontSize 11
}

actor "PC App\n(Dyno.App / Dyno.Core)" as App
box "STM32 firmware" #F4F9FF
participant "USB Controller\n(usbcontroller_main)" as USB
participant "Owning Task\n(e.g. ForceSensor)" as Task
participant "SessionController" as Session
end box

== Handshake — device-announced, version-checked ==

App -> USB : opens the port → CDC **DTR asserted** (SET_CONTROL_LINE_STATE)
note over USB
  _appReady = false
  → the device streams nothing yet
end note

loop every ~DEVICE_READY_ANNOUNCE_MS, until _appReady
    USB -> App : **USB_MSG_EVENT** / TASK_OFFSET_USB_CONTROLLER\nusb_device_ready_event{ USB_PROTOCOL_VERSION }
end

App -> USB : **USB_MSG_COMMAND** / TASK_OFFSET_USB_CONTROLLER\nUSB_CMD_ACK, body = host USB_PROTOCOL_VERSION
note over USB : HandleUsbLocalCommand()\ncompare host vs firmware version

alt versions match
    USB -> App : **USB_MSG_RESPONSE**  USB_RSP_OK\n(sets _appReady = true)
    USB -> App : **USB_MSG_EVENT** / TASK_OFFSET_SESSION_CONTROLLER\nsession_state_event{ in_session }  (state as it stands)
    note over App, USB
      Announced after **every** ack, changed or not. Sensor data only flows during a
      session, so a host connecting to a steady board — idle, or already mid-session —
      would otherwise wait on an edge that may never come, unable to tell an idle dyno
      from a dead one.
    end note
else mismatch
    USB -> App : **USB_MSG_RESPONSE**  USB_RSP_VERSION_MISMATCH\n(stays not-ready, keeps announcing)
end

note over App
  The host bounds this wait: no handshake within HandshakeTimeout (5 s)
  and it reports the device unresponsive — an open port proves nothing,
  since one opens against any board that enumerates. It keeps listening.
end note

== Keep-alive — the host polls a link that has gone quiet ==

loop every HeartbeatInterval (5 s), once handshaked
    App -> USB : **USB_MSG_COMMAND**  USB_CMD_ACK  (re-sent as a ping)
    USB -> App : **USB_MSG_RESPONSE**  USB_RSP_OK
    USB -> App : **USB_MSG_EVENT**  session_state_event{ in_session }\n(re-stated; the host raises a change event only if it moved)
end
note over App, USB
  USB_CMD_ACK doubles as the ping: the USB controller answers it itself, in any
  state, and re-applying it is a no-op — so no dedicated opcode is needed.
  Two unanswered pings ⇒ the host declares the link lost, but keeps polling, so a
  device that comes back is picked up without a reconnect.

  Re-stating the session state on each ack is what makes it self-healing: a host that
  declared the link lost drops its session state, while _appReady here stays set — so an
  edge-only announcement would never reach it again and a running session would look
  idle forever.
end note

== Host closes the port — the link ends (not to be confused with a dyno session) ==

App -> USB : CDC **DTR deasserted** (SET_CONTROL_LINE_STATE)
note over USB
  HandleHostDetach()
  _appReady = false; TX buffer + RX ring dropped
  → stops streaming into a port nobody reads,
    and starts announcing again for the next host
end note

== Reconnect — the host asks when nothing announces ==

note over App, USB
  Without the DTR signal above (an older build, or a host that never asserts DTR)
  a still-powered board stays _appReady and so never announces again — nothing is
  coming, and a purely announce-driven handshake would wait forever. So if no
  announcement arrives within HandshakeProbeInterval (1 s), the host asks directly.
end note

App -> USB : **USB_MSG_COMMAND**  USB_CMD_ACK  (unsolicited probe)
USB -> App : **USB_MSG_RESPONSE**  USB_RSP_OK\n(sets _appReady = true → streaming re-armed)

== Health & faults — whenever handshaked, session or not ==

note over USB, Task : sensor tasks sample continuously and fill their circular buffers,\nwhether or not a session is running

loop each Run() iteration, while _appReady
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_STREAM  task_monitor_output_data      (TASK_OFFSET_TASK_MONITOR)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_ERROR / USB_MSG_WARNING  task_error_data\n(task_offset + number packed in error_code)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_WARNING  WARNING_USB_TX_BATCH_DROPPED\n(ReportTxDropsIfDue)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_WARNING  WARNING_USB_{OPTICAL_ENCODER,FORCE_SENSOR,BPM,TASK_ERROR}_BUFFER_OVERFLOW\n(ReportBufferOverflowsIfDue)
end
note over App, USB
  Not sensor data, so not session-gated: a task dying or a stack running out
  is most worth seeing while the dyno sits idle. Draining the task-monitor
  queue unconditionally also stops it filling up between sessions.

  The overflow warnings name the buffer, per buffer, because which one it is *is* the
  diagnosis: one stream means that producer outran the drain, all four at once means
  this task stalled. Rate-limited to one per buffer per second — a reader a lap behind
  usually stays behind, and the report would otherwise add to the load that caused it.
  Both reports run *after* the drains, so a loss detected on this pass counts.
end note

== Sensor data — only while _appReady && a session is running ==

Session -> USB : in-session = true  (session started)
note over USB
  SkipBufferedSensorData()
  catch each reader up to its writer: what the sensor
  tasks buffered while idle predates the session, and
  would otherwise flush ahead of the live stream
end note

USB -> App : **USB_MSG_EVENT**  session_state_event{ in_session = 1 }
note right of App
  Framed **before** the samples below, so the start always
  reaches the host ahead of the data it explains: the app
  shows sensor readings only while a session is running, and
  would discard samples that arrived before the start event.
end note

loop each Run() iteration (drain & frame)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_STREAM  optical_encoder_output_data   (TASK_OFFSET_OPTICAL_ENCODER)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_STREAM  forcesensor_output_data       (active force-sensor offset)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_STREAM  bpm_output_data               (TASK_OFFSET_BPM_CONTROLLER)
end

Session -> USB : in-session = false  (session ended)
USB -> App : **USB_MSG_EVENT**  session_state_event{ in_session = 0 }\n(app clears the readouts — a stale number reads as a live one)
note over App, Session
  The session is the **only** gate on sensor data — there is no USB-logging
  on/off switch to get left in the wrong position. A host connected during a
  session always receives that session's data.

  An edge that falls while no host is acked is not lost: the next ack sets
  _sessionStateDue and the current state goes out then.
end note

== Host command — USB-controller-local (handled in place) ==

App -> USB : USB_MSG_COMMAND / TASK_OFFSET_USB_CONTROLLER\nopcode, msg_id (>= 1)
note over USB : HandleUsbLocalCommand() answers directly
USB -> App : USB_MSG_RESPONSE  echo opcode + msg_id, status

App -> USB : **USB_CMD_SET_SYSCONFIG**\nsysconfig_set_param_body{ param_id, raw_value }
note over USB
  sysconfig_set_raw() — range-checked (NaN/Inf rejected
  for floats); tasks read the store every loop pass, so
  it takes effect on the next one with no queue or wake-up
end note
USB -> App : USB_MSG_RESPONSE  USB_RSP_OK | USB_RSP_MALFORMED
note over App, USB
  Applied by the USB task itself — the store is plain RAM — so this OK is still a
  full-path ack, not a "queued" one. The board persists nothing: the host keeps the
  values and re-pushes them after every handshake, so a freshly-booted board runs the
  config.h defaults until it does.
end note

== Host command — routed to a task (full-path "non-posted" ack) ==

App -> USB : USB_MSG_COMMAND / e.g. TASK_OFFSET_FORCE_SENSOR_ADS1115\nopcode (FORCE_SENSOR_CMD_SET_DATA_RATE), msg_id (>= 1), body
note over USB
  DispatchFrame() → QueueForTaskOffset()
  Ack is **non-posted**: the USB task sends
  no RESPONSE here — the owning task will.
end note

alt route exists & body fits & queue not full
    USB -> Task : usb_task_command{ opcode, msg_id, body }\n(owning task's command queue)
    note over Task : ProcessCommands() → ApplyCommand()\n(real device write, e.g. ADS1115 setRate)
    Task -> USB : usb_task_completion{ task_offset, opcode, msg_id, status }\n(shared completion queue)
    note over USB : ProcessCompletions()\n(msg_id 0 = internal command → dropped, no ack)
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_RESPONSE  echo opcode + msg_id, **real applied status**
else no route / body too big / queue full
    USB -> App : USB_MSG_RESPONSE\nUSB_RSP_NOT_SUPPORTED | USB_RSP_MALFORMED | USB_RSP_QUEUE_FULL
end

== Transfer accounting — closes every CDC transfer (v7) ==

note over USB
  TransmitBatch()
  stamp the trailer onto the pending records,
  then hand the whole buffer to CDC_Transmit_FS
end note

USB -> App : **USB_MSG_STATUS** / TASK_OFFSET_USB_CONTROLLER\nusb_tx_batch_trailer{ batch_seq, batch_len }

note over App, USB
  Makes byte loss **attributable**. The SOF/CRC envelope already says bytes went missing;
  it cannot say whether they were lost above the driver or below it, and those are opposite
  bugs. Counting the bytes that arrive between two trailers against batch_len answers it:
    • short            ⇒ the firmware framed and submitted bytes that never landed
    • batch_seq gap    ⇒ a whole accepted transfer vanished
    • adds up, but the parser still resyncs ⇒ the device framed a record wrong to begin with

  It is a **trailer, not a header**: the loss it was built to diagnose eats the *leading* bytes
  of a transfer, exactly where a marker would be destroyed by the thing it is meant to measure.

  batch_seq advances **only on acceptance**, so a batch the driver refused burns no number and
  cannot be misread as a transfer lost in flight — that case is WARNING_USB_TX_BATCH_DROPPED.

  The host consumes the trailer as framing and never publishes it as a message
  (StreamParser / BatchAccounting).
end note

note over App, Task
  **Framing — both directions.** Every record is wrapped so the receiver can resync:
  [uint16 USB_FRAME_SOF][usb_msg_header_t][payload][uint16 CRC-16/CCITT-FALSE].
  The CRC covers the header + payload bytes; the SOF and the CRC field itself are excluded.
  A receiver scans to a SOF, checks the CRC, and on a mismatch treats that SOF as spurious —
  so a cut-off record is *detected*, not inferred from a payload that looks wrong.
  (v5: outbound records used to be unframed, on the assumption USB-CDC is reliable.)

  **Correlation.** msg_id ties each RESPONSE to its COMMAND; msg_id 0 is firmware-internal (no host ack).

  **Contract.** All struct/enum layouts are generated from messages_public.yaml (single source of
  truth); USB_PROTOCOL_VERSION (currently 7) guards that the host and firmware agree at runtime.
end note

@enduml
